04259nam a22004815i 9780226045634DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20072006ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226045634  a(DE-B1597)522728  a(OCoLC)842603665  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQ180.55.M6 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a520.92a520/.921 aBiagioli, Mario, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGalileo's Instruments of Credit :bTelescopes, Images, Secrecy /cMario Biagioli. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2007] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (316 p.) :b16 halftones, 3 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: From Brass Instruments to Textual Supplements -- tChapter one: Financing the Aura -- tChapter two: Replication or Monopoly? -- tChapter three: Between Risk and Credit -- tChapter four: The Supplemental Economy of Galileo’s Book of Nature -- tEpilogue: Unintended Differences -- tAcknowledgments -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn six short years, Galileo Galilei went from being a somewhat obscure mathematics professor running a student boarding house in Padua to a star in the court of Florence to the recipient of dangerous attention from the Inquisition for his support of Copernicanism. In that brief period, Galileo made a series of astronomical discoveries that reshaped the debate over the physical nature of the heavens: he deeply modified the practices and status of astronomy with the introduction of the telescope and pictorial evidence, proposed a radical reconfiguration of the relationship between theology and astronomy, and transformed himself from university mathematician into court philosopher. Galileo's Instruments of Credit proposes radical new interpretations of several key episodes of Galileo's career, including his early telescopic discoveries of 1610, the dispute over sunspots, and the conflict with the Holy Office over the relationship between Copernicanism and Scripture. Galileo's tactics during this time shifted as rapidly as his circumstances, argues Mario Biagioli, and the pace of these changes forced him to respond swiftly to the opportunities and risks posed by unforeseen inventions, further discoveries, and the interventions of his opponents. Focusing on the aspects of Galileo's scientific life that extend beyond the framework of court culture and patronage, Biagioli offers a revisionist account of the different systems of exchanges, communication, and credibility at work in various phases of Galileo's career. Galileo's Instruments of Credit will find grateful readers among scholars of science studies, historical epistemology, visual studies, Galilean science, and late Renaissance astronomy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAstronomy. 0aScience. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agalileo, science, florence, padua, copernicanism, astronomy, history, inquisition, religion, heresy, doctrine, telescope, theology, court philosopher, university, mathematician, sunspots, holy office, scripture, discovery, invention, patronage, culture, exchange, communication, credibility, theory, renaissance, epistemology, visual studies, scientific instruments, authority, distance, medicean stars, book of nature, nonfiction.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226045634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226045634/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles